Mammals Life History

Make R identify the -999 as an NA.

  1. Where are the NAs? This is important to keep in mind as you build plots.
life_history %>% 
  purrr::map_df(~ sum(is.na(.))) %>% 
  tidyr::gather(variables, num_nas) %>%

ggplot()

For the questions below, try to use the aesthetics you have learned to make visually appealing and informative plots. Make sure to include labels for the axes and titles.

  1. What is the relationship between newborn body mass and gestation? Make a scatterplot that shows this relationship.
options(scipen=999)
life_history %>% 
  ggplot(aes(newborn, gestation)) + 
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 673 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. You should notice that because of the outliers in newborn mass, we need to make some changes. We didnt talk about this in lab, but you can use scale_x_log10() as a layer to correct for this issue. This will log transform the y-axis values.
life_history %>% 
  ggplot(aes(newborn, gestation)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10()+
  labs(title = "Gestation Time vs Newborn Mass", "Newborn Mass (g)", "Gestation (months)")
## Warning: Removed 673 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

##Voila, a scatterplot!

  1. Now that you have the basic plot, color the points by taxonomic order.
life_history %>% 
  ggplot(aes(newborn, gestation, color = order)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10()+
  labs(title = "Gestation Time vs Newborn Mass", "Newborn Mass (g)", "Gestation (months)")
## Warning: Removed 673 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Lastly, make the size of the points proportional to body mass.
life_history %>% 
  ggplot(aes(newborn, gestation, color = order, size = mass)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "Gestation Time vs Newborn Mass", "Newborn Mass (g)", "Gestation (months)", color = "Taxanomic Order") +
  scale_size(guide = "none")
## Warning: Removed 691 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

##Added some color to each order and relatice size to each dot.

  1. Make a plot that shows the range of lifespan by order.
life_history %>% 
  ggplot(aes(order, max_life, fill = order)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(title = "Lifespan for each Taxanomic Order", x = "Taxanomic Order", y = "Lifespan (months)", fill = "Taxanomic Order")
